         = Stanier 8F 2-8-0 No. 48479.jpg\n|caption         = Stanier 8F No. 48476 at Lostock Hall shed, late July 1968\n|designer        = [[William Stanier]]\n|builder         = {{plainlist|\n* LMS [[Crewe Works]] - (137)\n* LMS [[Horwich Works]] - (75)\n* [[North British Locomotive Co.]] - (208)\n* LNER [[Darlington Works]] - (53)\n* LNER [[Doncaster Works]] - (50)\n* GWR [[Swindon Works]] - (80)\n* [[Vulcan Foundry]] - (69)\n* SR [[Brighton Works]] - (93)\n* SR [[Eastleigh Works]] - (23)\n* SR [[Ashford Works]] - (14)\n* [[Beyer, Peacock and Company|Beyer, Peacock & Co.]] for [[Railway Executive Committee|REC]] and [[Ministry of Supply|MoS]] orders)}} - (50)\n|builddate       = 1935\u20131946\n|totalproduction = 852\n|whytetype       = [[2-8-0]]\n|uicclass        = 1\u2032D h2\n|gauge           = {{Track gauge|ussg|allk=on}}\n|leadingdiameter = {{convert|3|ft|3+1/2|in|m|3|abbr=on}}\n|driverdiameter  =  {{convert|4|ft|8+1/2|in|m|3|abbr=on}}\n|wheelbase       = {{convert|52|ft|7+3/4|in|m|3|abbr=on}}\n|length          = {{convert|63|ft|0+1/2|in|m|2|abbr=on}}\n|locoweight      = {{convert|72.10|LT|t ST|abbr=on}}\n|fueltype        = [[Coal]]  \n|fuelcap         = {{convert|9|LT|t ST|1|abbr=on}}\n|watercap        = {{convert|4000|impgal|abbr=on}}\n|boiler          = LMS type 3C\n|boilerpressure  = {{convert|225|lbf/in2|MPa|2|abbr=on|lk=on}}\n|firearea        = {{convert|28+1/2|sqft|abbr=on}}\n|tubearea        = {{convert|1479|sqft|abbr=on}}\n|fireboxarea     = {{convert|171|sqft|abbr=on}}\n|superheaterarea = {{convert|215|\u2013|245|sqft|abbr=on}}\n|cylindercount   = Two, outside \n|cylindersize    = {{convert|18+1/2|x|28|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n|tractiveeffort  = {{convert|32440|lbf|kN|2|abbr=on|lk=on}}\n|operator        = {{unbulleted list|[[London, Midland and Scottish Railway]]|[[London and North Eastern Railway]]|[[War Department (United Kingdom)|War Department]]|[[Trans-Iranian Railway]]|[[Palestine Railways]]|[[Egyptian State Railways]]|[[Iraqi State Railways]]|[[Ferrovie dello Stato]]|[[T\u00fcrkiye Cumhuriyeti Devlet Demiryollar\u0131]]|[[British Railways]]|[[Israel Railways]]{{sfn|Hughes|1981| pp=122\u2013124}}}}\n|powerclass      = LMS & BR: 7F, later 8F\n|axleloadclass   = [[Route Availability]] 6\n|withdrawndate   = BR: 1960\u20131968\n|disposition     = 12 preserved, 2 dumped in Turkey but still extant, 1 parts donor, 23 lost at sea, remainder scrapped\n}}\nThe [[London Midland and Scottish Railway]]'s '''8F class''' [[2-8-0]] heavy freight locomotive is a class of [[steam locomotive]] designed for hauling heavy freight. 852 were built between 1935 and 1946 (not all to LMS order), as a freight version of [[William Stanier]]'s successful [[LMS Stanier Class 5 4-6-0|Black Five]], and the class saw extensive service overseas during and after the [[Second World War]].\n\n== Background ==\nLMS freight traction suffered from the adoption of the [[Midland Railway]]'s small engine policy which had left it with trains double-headed by underpowered 0-6-0s supplemented by inadequate [[LMS Garratt|Garratts]] and [[LMS Class 7F 0-8-0|Fowler 7F]] [[0-8-0]]s.\n\nThe 8F design incorporated the two-cylinder arrangement of the Black Fives. They were initially classified 7F, but this was later changed to the more familiar 8F.\n\nOn the outbreak of the [[Second World War]], the design was chosen to become the country's standard freight design, reprising the role the [[GCR Class 8K]] had in the [[World War I|First World War]].  The [[War Department (United Kingdom)|War Department]] had 208 8Fs built by [[Beyer Peacock]] and [[North British Locomotive Company]] and [[requisitioned]] 51 more.\n\nStanier 8F production for the WD continued until 1943, when the cheaper [[WD Austerity 2-8-0]] was introduced.  Production for British domestic use continued until 1946.\n\n== Construction ==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Order\n! Builder\n! Delivered\n! Quantity\n! Original Numbers\n! Notes\n|-\n| London, Midland & Scottish Railway\n| LMS Crewe Works\n| 