{"title_page": "Orbita (collective)", "text_new": "'''Orbita''' is a Latvian Russian-language poetry collective formed in Riga, Latvia in 1999.\n\nOrbita was originally founded by five members: Artur Punte, Seymon Khanin, Vladimir Svetlov, Sergej Timofejev, and Zhorzh Uallik. At present, all founders (excluding Zhorzh Uallik) are active in the group. Additionally, the group includes a myriad of other Latvian and Russian artists and creatives spanning many genres and such forms of art as photography.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Platt|first=Kevin M. F.|title=Global Russian Cultures.|publisher=The University of Wisconsin Press, 2019|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> Orbita is heavily involved in Latvian literary culture. In fact, all of the poetry presented by Orbita is written in both Russian and Latvian.<ref name=\":3\" /> The group has organized five of their own \"Word in Motion\" poetry festivals between 2001 and 2011, and has published an anthology of Russian poetry showcasing various contemporary Latvian poets.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Platt|first=Kevin M. F. \"About the Translation.\"|title=Orbita: The Project|publisher=Jean Boase-Beier (ed.). Cornwall: Arc Publications, 2018. 9-10. Print.|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== Artistry ==\nAs a group, Orbita is known for its use of [[free verse]], which is quite different from classical and even contemporary Russian-language poetry. Orbita is also known for their extensive ventures into [[video poetry]] and [[performance poetry]].<ref name=\":1\">Platt, Kevin M. F. \"Introduction.\". ''Hit Parade: The Orbita Group''.\" Platt, Kevin M. F. (ed.). Ugly Duckling Press, 2015. Print.</ref>\n\nMuch of the group's work observes and explores many themes relating to geography, borders, and the movement (both temporally and metaphorically) between these borders.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Reception ==\nOrbita has been cited as an influential force in the shaping of contemporary Latvian poetry.<ref name=\":4\">Fowler, Steven J. \"Introduction.\". ''Orbita: The Project''. Jean Boase-Beier (ed.). Cornwall: Arc Publications, 2018. 13-14. Print.</ref> The group has been well-received not only in Latvia, but in many other European and North American countries as well.<ref name=\":4\" /> This reception includes things like exhibition and publishing of the group's works in festivals across these countries.\n\n== Recognition ==\nAs a group, Orbita has received the following awards:\n\n* Annual Literary Prize of the Union of Latvian Writers - 2005<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\">Fedorova, Natalia. \u201cOrbita.\u201d ''ELMCIP'', 1 Jan. 1970, elmcip.net/node/8428.</ref>\n* Annual Prize for the Best Photography Album - 2006<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n* Annual Prize for the Best Photograph Exhibit - 2007<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Poetry]]\n[[Category:Latvian poets]]\n[[Category:1999 establishments]]\n", "text_old": "'''Orbita''' is a Latvian Russian-language poetry collective formed in Riga, Latvia in 1999.\n\nOrbita was originally founded by five members: Artur Punte, Seymon Khanin, Vladimir Svetlov, Sergej Timofejev, and Zhorzh Uallik. At present, all founders (excluding Zhorzh Uallik) are active in the group. Additionally, the group includes a myriad of other Latvian and Russian artists and creatives spanning many genres and such forms of art as photography.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Platt|first=Kevin M. F.|title=Global Russian Cultures.|publisher=The University of Wisconsin Press, 2019|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> Orbita is heavily involved in Latvian literary culture. In fact, all of the poetry presented by Orbita is written in both Russian and Latvian.<ref name=\":3\" /> The group has organized five of their own \"Word in Motion\" poetry festivals between 2001 and 2011, and has published an anthology of Russian poetry showcasing various contemporary Latvian poets.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Platt|first=Kevin M. F. \"About the Translation.\"|title=Orbita: The Project|publisher=Jean Boase-Beier (ed.). Cornwall: Arc Publications, 2018. 9-10. Print.|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> \n\n== Artistry ==\nAs a group, Orbita is known for its use of [[free verse]], which is quite different from classical and even contemporary Russian-language poetry. Orbita is also known for their extensive ventures into [[video poetry]] and [[performance poetry]].<ref name=\":1\">Platt, Kevin M. F. \"Introduction.\". ''Hit Parade: The Orbita Group''.\" Platt, Kevin M. F. (ed.). Ugly Duckling Press, 2015. Print.</ref>\n\nMuch of the group's work observes and explores many themes relating to geography, borders, and the movement (both temporally and metaphorically) between these borders.<ref name=\":1\" />\n== Reception ==\nOrbita has been cited as an influential force in the shaping of contemporary Latvian poetry.<ref name=\":4\">Fowler, Steven J. \"Introduction.\". ''Orbita: The Project''. Jean Boase-Beier (ed.). Cornwall: Arc Publications, 2018. 13-14. Print.</ref> The group has been well-received not only in Latvia, but in many other European and North American countries as well.<ref name=\":4\" /> This reception includes things like exhibition and publishing of the group's works in festivals across these countries.\n\n== Recognition ==\nAs a group, Orbita has received the following awards:\n\n* Annual Literary Prize of the Union of Latvian Writers - 2005<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\">Fedorova, Natalia. \u201cOrbita.\u201d ''ELMCIP'', 1 Jan. 1970, elmcip.net/node/8428.</ref>\n* Annual Prize for the Best Photography Album - 2006<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n* Annual Prize for the Best Photograph Exhibit - 2007<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== References ==\n\n\n\n[[Category:Poetry]]\n[[Category:Latvian poets]]\n[[Category:1999 establishments]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orbita_(collective)"}
